- t21 Communal Matters and Scientific Facts: -- t22 Imagining Resistance to Trump through the Networked Branding of the National Park Service -- tPart V. How Do We Imagine Our Social Connections with a Larger Community -- t23 Moving to a Bollywood Beat, “Born in the USA” Goes My Indian Heart? -- t24 “Our” Hamilton: -- t25 Participatory Action in Humans of New York -- t26 A Vision for Black Lives in the Black Radical Tradition -- tPart VI. How Do We Bring an Imaginative Dimension to Our Real-World Spaces and Places -- t27 “Without My City, Where Is My Past?” -- t28 Reimagining and Mediating a Progressive Christian South -- t29 Tzina: Symphony of Longing: -- t30 What’s Civic about Aztlán? -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow popular culture is engaged by activists to effect emancipatory political change One cannot change the world unless one can imagine what a better world might look like. Civic imagination is the capacity to conceptualize alternatives to current cultural, social, political, or economic conditions; it also requires the ability to see oneself as a civic agent capable of making change, as a participant in a larger democratic culture. Popular Culture and the Civic Imagination represents a call for greater clarity about what we’re fighting for—not just what we’re fighting against. Across more than thirty examples from social movements around the world, this casebook proposes “civic imagination” as a framework that can help us identify, support, and practice new kinds of communal participation. As the contributors demonstrate, young people, in particular, are turning to popular culture—from Beyoncé to Bollywood, from Smokey Bear to Hamilton, from comic books to VR—for the vernacular through which they can express their discontent with current conditions.A young activist uses YouTube to speak back against J. K. Rowling in the voice of Cho Chang in order to challenge the superficial representation of Asian Americans in children’s literature. Murals in Los Angeles are employed to construct a mythic imagination of Chicano identity. Twitter users have turned to #BlackGirlMagic to highlight the black radical imagination and construct new visions of female empowerment. In each instance, activists demonstrate what happens when the creative energies of fans are infused with deep political commitment, mobilizing new visions of what a better democracy might look like.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCivics. 0aPopular culture. 0aSocial change. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aAlarcón, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanet-Weiser, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBillard, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallison, Candis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncombe, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElsayed, Yomna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGipson, Brooklyne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenkins, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenkins, Henry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKelvin, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Donna Do-own, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu